{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Autonomous agents, like autonomous nations, are able to govern themselves.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "They are not controlled by external forces or manipulated by outside agents.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "They set goals for themselves, establishing principles for their choices and actions, and they are able to act in accord with those principles.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Just as deliberative democracies legislate so as to balance competing interests, autonomous agents deliberate to reach some consistency among their competing desires and values.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "And just as good governments create their laws in the open without undue influence by covert factions, autonomous agents form their principles for action through conscious deliberation without undue influence by unconscious forces.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Autonomous agents are self-controlled not weak-willed, self-aware not self-deceptive.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Indeed, we believe we are, for the most part, autonomous agents.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "However, there are threats to this commonsense belief.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Some philosophers argue that if causal determinism is true then we lack free will and hence are not fully autonomous or responsible for our actions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "One might also worry that if certain explanations of the mind-body relationship are true, then our conscious deliberations are epiphenomenal in such a way that we are not really autonomous.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "But other threats to autonomy are less often discussed, threats that are not metaphysical or political but psychological.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "These are threats based on putative facts about human psychology that suggest we do not govern our behavior according to principles we have consciously chosen.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "For instance, if our behavior were governed primarily by unconscious Freudian desires rather than by our reflectively considered desires, we would be much less autonomous than we presume.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Or if our behaviors were the result of a history of Skinnerian reinforcement rather than conscious consideration, our actions would be shaped by our environment more than by our principles.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Since the influence of Freud and Skinner has waned, we might feel we have escaped such threats to our autonomy from the psychology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "But, as I will explain below, more recent and viable theories and evidence from social psychology pose significant threats to autonomous agency.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "On most conceptions of autonomous agency it clearly requires freedom of action, which is the ability to act on one's desires without external constraint.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "But such freedom is not sufficient for autonomy, since agents may also be internally constrained or influenced by external factors in ways more subtle than constraint or coercion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "For instance, agents may act on addictions, phobias, or even strong passions that they would prefer not to move them.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Or agents may be influenced by subtle manipulations (e.g., advertising) or by unrecognized situational factors (e.g., peer pressure) that, had the agents known about them, they would not want to influence them.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "These cases suggest that autonomy requires more than simply being free to act on one's desires; it also requires some measure of internal consistency among one's desires and values and some capacity to understand oneself and one's situation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "We adult humans are autonomous in ways that young children and animals are not.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "This is in part because we are often moved not simply by our strongest urge in a given situation; we are also able to consider our immediate desires in terms of our long-term goals, including our moral and social obligations.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "However, it would be inefficient, if not impossible, to reflect on our goals and obligations every time we act.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "Rather, we tend to deliberate about such matters calmly and reflectively to establish the ways we hope to respond without much reflection when faced with the relevant situations.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Hence, autonomous agency requires the ability to form and act on principles.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "The formation of these principles should occur through conscious deliberation without the influence of any unconscious motivations the agent would reject if she knew about them.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "And the principles should be as internally consistent as possible so that the agent does not betray some of her own principles by acting on others.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "Given this conception of autonomy, we can see that an agent's autonomy is threatened to the extent that she is ignorant of factors that lead her to act against her principles-i.e., were she to recognize these factors, she would reject them.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU30": {
      "text": "Similarly, an agent's autonomy is threatened by rationalization: cases in which the agent finds herself acting against her consciously chosen principles but retrospectively comes up with reasons to justify her action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU31": {
      "text": "Here, actions inconsistent with prior principles are explained (to herself and others) in terms of post hoc principles adjusted to fit the actions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU32": {
      "text": "Of course, we are all subject to cases of ignorance and rationalization.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU33": {
      "text": "But are we subject to these challenges to our autonomy to a greater extent than we realize?",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
